<div class="container shadow ">
  <div class="section-header">
    <h1 class="headers"><i class="material-icons" id="green-font">explore</i> Hobbies</h1>
  </div>
  <div class="section-container">
    <br>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-2">
        <%= image_tag 'https://www.raspberrypi.org/app/uploads/2015/08/raspberry-pi-logo.png', class: 'hobbies' %>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-10">
        <h2>Robotics</h2>
        I'm pretty interested in robotics and machine learning. I've built a couple of different rovers that manuever based on visual and auditory input.
        I typically use a <b>RaspberryPi</b> because they are user-friendly and have a lot of available RAM. I have also used Arduinos for robotics projects, but
        they are often limited in space.
        <br>
        <br>
        The only machine learning I've done is a course on Coursera taught by Andrew Ng along with following <b>OpenCV & Tensorflow guides.</b> One of my long term
        goals is to build a robot that includes image classification in order to potentially have it tackle tasks that it was not hardwired to handle.
        <br>
        <br>
        The RaspberryPi has given me a great baseline knowledge of working systems. I've used the RaspberryPi to build all types of projects for friends or
        clients. I built an advertising and scheduling kiosk for a local Hockey team in Madison, WI. And I built a automatic video player for a live demo
        display for a small gutter guard installation company.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-2">
        <%= image_tag 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/af/Tux.png', class: 'hobbies' %>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-10">
        <h2>Linux</h2>
        <b>I love Linux.</b> When I first downloaded Ubuntu, I was a little turned off by the UI (being a Windows user my whole life). But then I installed Linux
        Mint and fell in love. Since then, I've converted all my machines into Linux boxes. A few of them are Ubuntu because it's well supported but most
        run the Mint distro.
        <br>
        <br>
        I've also read quite a few books on Kali Linux in order to study Pen Testing with Metasploitable. Pen testing is definitely a headache and any real world
        scenarios require a lot of patience. I usually prefer to have concrete evidence of progress in order to feel motivated. So, I took a step back from
        pen testing unless it's too check the security of my own applications.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-lg-2">
        <%= image_tag 'https://www.apogeerockets.com/includes/templates/edify/images/logo/Apogee%20Logo%20sm.png', class: 'hobbies' %>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-10">
        <h2>Model Rockets</h2>
        <%= image_tag '/hobbies/modelrocket.jpg', id: 'modelrocket' %>
        Lately, I've been really interested in <b>model rocketry.</b> It's a lot of fun and it provides me with a good mixture of challenges and relaxation. My
        most recent model "The Eclipse" is going to be shot off a day before the actual Eclipse down in Illinois. I'll post a photo so you can see
        just how big it is!
        <br>
        <br>
        I really enjoy building projects that have an impact in the physical world. It's a nice reprieve when 99% of my work is virtual. Someday, I'd like to
        bring my software development skills somewhere physical. Machines and automata have been at the heart of programming since the beginning. Now that most
        of our tasks can be handled online, people have sort of drifted away from its origins. I believe that - with the advent of the Machine Learning boom -
        we are going to see computers interacting with the real world much more often. I'd love to be a part of that!
        <br>
        <br>
        I guess what I'm trying to say is: building rockets is just the first step. I plan on eventually introducing GPS coordinate tracking systems along with
        some more complex electronic "innards" of the payload. It would be really cool to overcome the technological challenges for something that literally
        explodes itself into the air.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
